uate breastmilk intake in an infant?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infrequent stools with dark concentrated urine","Weight gain along the 50th centile","Return to birth weight at two weeks of age","Six pale wet diapers per day","Frequent soft yellow stools"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe signs of inadequate breastmilk intake include \u003Cstrong\u003Einfrequent stools with dark concentrated urine\u003C/strong\u003E. These indicate dehydration and insufficient milk intake. The stool frequency decreases and becomes harder due to the body conserving water, while urine becomes more concentrated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESigns of adequate intake include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight gain along the 50th centile\u003C/strong\u003E is normal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReturn to birth weight at two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate timing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix pale wet diapers per day\u003C/strong\u003E (beyond the first week) indicates good hydration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrequent soft yellow stools\u003C/strong\u003E are typical in well-fed breastfed infants\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther signs of inadequate intake may include lethargy, poor feeding and failure to gain appropriate weight.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inadequate breastmilk intake is indicated by infrequent, hard stools and reduced wet diapers with concentrated urine.","Normal breastfed infants should regain birth weight by 2 weeks.","Adequate breastfeeding results in 6-8 pale, wet diapers and frequent soft yellow stools daily."],"references":["Australian Breastfeeding Association. Is my baby getting enough breastmilk? | Australian Breastfeeding Association [Internet]. w